description.narrative:
Oxfam Novib's Finance for Development (F4D) Theory of Change is part of our overall Strategic Partnership with the Dutch government. Through the F4D program we strive to reduce extreme economic inequality via fiscal justice. Fiscal justice is about people being able to exercise their rights by monitoring and influencing fiscal systems to make them fair, to mobilize greater revenue and increase and improve spending for quality public services for all. Deliberate political and economic choices can lead to less economic inequality, enhanced social justice and better functioning democracies. To ensure a strong link between the global work and the southerncampaigning and influencing work we provide technical tax related trainings to local civil society organizations, provide national and international coalitions with technical and financial support, monitor the implementation of tax policies and make proposals forimprovements, engage with citizens and the media to increase the public pressure on governments and multinational corporations.
The Fair Tax Monitor (FTM) is a unique evidence-based advocacy tool that identifies the main bottlenecks within tax systems and provides strong evidence for advocacy work at national and international level. In the next 2 years hands on support will be provided to strengthen the advocacy journeys of the countries based on their national research findings. Hence, they will be supported to implement the research and to develop influencing strategies easy to understand messages based on the research. Via peer/expert review workshops linking <(>&<)> learning and alliance building are facilitated.
Roving Flexible Campaign support is available to strengthen partners# influencing and campaigning capacity to strengthen the interaction between our global and local campaign work. This short-term additional support comes next to regular capacity building support and allows partners to actively participate our the globalcampaign She Pays the Price or in global campaign moments when our global inequality reports are launched.
Apart from working withSOMO, to achieve the long-term outcome on a global scale, Oxfam works together with numerous partners, including Eurodad, Global Alliance for Tax Justice (GATJ), and Tax Justice Network Nederland (TJN-NL). Oxfam Novib provides influencing support and gender support to Oxfam country offices and partners in Morocco, Egypt, Palestine, Niger, Nigeria, Uganda, Pakistan, Cambodia and Vietnam.
Under the Global Inequality campaign Oxfam Novib, together with other Oxfams and partners, address the Dutch government, other governments, international institutions, regional bodies and the private sector to hold them account for their contribution to rising extremeinequality and poverty. Particularly in the Netherlands, we will continue to advocate for measures that should end the role played by the Netherlands as a global corporate tax haven and that should contribute to ending a harmful global corporate tax race to the bottom. This work includes awareness raising on tax justice among Dutch citizens through on-going communication/engagement with the Dutch audience.

participating-org.narrative: Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994. Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies. Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy. Oxfam Novib’s the Hague office contributes towards this project’s implementation.
